      "parts": [
        {
          "label": "(i)",
          "marks": 3,
          "answer": "Proof that $(x-4)^2 - 2x > 9$",
          "markAllocation": [
            {
              "code": "M1",
              "type": "M",
              "value": 1,
              "criterion": "Attempts to expand $(x-4)^2$ and work from form $(x-4)^2 - 2x > 9$ to form a 3TQ on one side of an equation or an inequality."
            },
            {
              "code": "A1",
              "type": "A",
              "value": 1,
              "criterion": "Achieves both $x^2-10x+25$ and $(x-5)^2$. Allow $(x-5)^2$ written as $(x-5)(x-5)$."
            },
            {
              "code": "A1*",
              "type": "A",
              "value": 1,
              "criterion": "For a correct proof. Eg \"square numbers are greater than or equal to zero\", hence (as $x \\in \\mathbb{R}$), $(x-5)^2 \\ge 0 \\Rightarrow (x-4)^2 - 2x > 9$. This requires (1) Correct algebra throughout, (2) a correct explanation concerning square numbers and (3) a reference back to the original statement. Answers via $b^2-4ac$ are unlikely to be correct. Whilst it is true that there is only one root and therefore it touches the x-axis, it does not show that it is always positive. The explanation could involve a sketch of $y=(x-5)^2$ but it must be accurate with a minimum on the +ve x axis with some statement alluding to why this shows $(x-5)^2 \\ge 0$."
            }
          ],
          "guidance": "A proof starting with the given statement. Approaches via odd and even numbers will usually not score anything. They would need to proceed using the main scheme via $(2m-4)^2 - 2(2m) > 9$ and $(2m+1-4)^2 - 2(2m+1) > 9$. Alt to (i) via contradiction: M1 For setting up the contradiction 'Assume that there is an x such that $(x-4)^2 - 2x < 9 \\Rightarrow x^2-10x+25 < 0$. A1 $(x-5)^2 < 0$. A1* This is not true as square numbers are always greater than or equal to 0, hence $(x-4)^2 - 2x > 9$. Alt to part (i) States $(x-5)^2 \\ge 0 \\Rightarrow x^2-10x+25 \\ge 0 \\Rightarrow x^2-8x+16 \\ge 2x+9 \\Rightarrow (x-4)^2 - 2x > 9$. M1 States $(x-5)^2 \\ge 0$ and attempts to expand. There is no explanation required here. A1 Rearranges to reach $x^2-8x+16 \\ge 2x+9$. A1* Reaches the given answer $(x-4)^2 - 2x > 9$ with no errors."
        },
        {
          "label": "(ii)",
          "marks": 1,
          "answer": "Shows that $n^2+n+1$ is not prime for a value of $n$",
          "markAllocation": [
            {
              "code": "B1",
              "type": "B",
              "value": 1,
              "criterion": "Shows that it is not true for a value of n. This requires a calculation (and value found) with a minimal statement that it is not true. Eg. '$6^2+6+1=43$ which is not prime' or '$5^2+5+1=33 \\times$'."
            }
          ],
          "guidance": "Condone sloppily expressed proofs. Eg. '$7^2+7+1=43 \\times 3 = 129$ which is not prime'. Condone implied proofs where candidates write $5^2+5+1=33$ which has a factor of 11. If there are lots of calculations mark positively. Only one value is required to be found (with the relevant statement) to score the B1. The calculation cannot be incorrect. Eg. $3^2+3+1=10$ which is not prime."
        }
      ]
